The '''Committee on Accounting Procedure''' (CAP) was the first private sector organization that had the task of setting accounting standards in the United States. It was a committee run by the American Institute of Accountants (now known as the [[American Institute of Certified Public Accountants]]).<ref>Spiceland, David; Sepe, James; Nelson, Mark; & Tomassini, Lawrence (2009). ''Intermediate Accounting'' (5th Edition). [[McGraw Hill|McGraw-Hill/Irwin]]. p. 9. {{ISBN|978-0-07-352687-4}}.</ref> CAP is the predecessor of the [[Accounting Principles Board]], itself a predecessor to the [[Financial Accounting Standards Board]]. Its formation and activities were early efforts to rationalize and legitimize the reporting of business performance. However, it is widely regarded as having failed.
[[George O. May]] was vice chairman of the committee from 1937 to 1945.[http://fisher.osu.edu/departments/accounting-and-mis/the-accounting-hall-of-fame/membership-in-hall/george-oliver-may/]
The committee published [[Accounting Research Bulletins]].
