'''Crystal River Engineering Inc.''' was an American technology company best known for their pioneering work in [[Head-related transfer function|HRTF]] based real-time [[Binaural recording|binaural]], or 3D sound processing hardware and software. The company was founded in 1989 by Scott Foster after he received a contract from [[NASA]] to create the audio component of VIEW (Virtual Environment Workstation Project), a [[Virtual Reality]] based training simulator for astronauts. Crystal River Engineering was acquired by [[Aureal|Aureal Semiconductor]] in 1996.

Crystal River's innovations in the field of real-time 3D audio processing were published in a series of papers<ref>http://humansystems.arc.nasa.gov/groups/ACD/personnel_view.php?personnel_id=372</ref> by NASA's [[Elizabeth Wenzel]] and Crystal River's Scott Foster.

